n<p>I used the following scripts in Powershell as Administrator after necessary Windows Defender updates to remove apps that consume memory:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"\">PowerShell app removal code</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>I then disabled memory-intensive services:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"\">PowerShell app removal code</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>To optimise performance from Windows, I disabled hibernation, set power settings to High Performance mode, and prevented sleep when plugged in:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"\">PowerShell app performance settings code</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>To reduce RAM usage by the GUI:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Start &gt; type &quot;this PC&quot; &gt; Right click &quot;This PC&quot; &gt; Properties &gt; Advanced system settings &gt; Advanced tab</li>\n<li>Performance &gt; Settings... &gt; &quot;Adjust for best performance&quot; in the Visual Effects tab</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I also changed the page file size:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Advanced tab &gt; Virtual memory &gt; Change...</li>\n<li>Custom size: Initial: 6144MB, Maximum 8192MB &gt; Set &gt; OK &gt; OK</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I installed <a href=\"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/wsl/install\">WSL2</a> to install Linux on my RAM-constrained hardware without needing to run a virtual machine (VM).</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"\">PowerShell enable dism</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Now what?</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Learning Curve</strong>:</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Challenges</strong>:</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n<h2>Artifacts</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://claude.ai/public/artifacts/af8635e3-14e0-426a-bb4b-c7b11dec1efa\">Claude: Building a Career-Boosting Homelab Development Server</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h2>References</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/wsl/install\">How to install Linux on Windows with WSL</a></li>\n</ul>\n<hr/><!--$--><!--/$--></main><footer class=\"mt-24 border-t border-zinc-100 px-0 py-4 dark:border-zinc-800\"><div class=\"flex items-center justify-between\"><a href=\"htt